commitMessage:"VersionUtil: Improve Android memory usage

The Android runtime implements Class.getResourceAsStream() with a very
memory-intensive cache
commitDate:"2025-04-17 08:01:29":
which holds the entire contents of the class's
.jar in memory.

A large Android app that uses Jackson will consume double the memory
today. Since memory is very tight on most Android devices
lastCommitId:"96e0fa79a473f725b8f07d18ba:
this diff
adds an alternative method to get version info for a package.

In specific
mergeBranchCommitId:null}: we now generate a class\ncom.fasterxml.jackson.core.json.PackageVersion at compile time.  At\nrun time
column7: VersionUtil now checks the class's package to see if there's\na class named 'PackageVersion'
column9: reads its 'VERSION' static\nfield for the Version data for the package.  (If not
column10:
we still use
the existing VERSION.txt resource code as a fallback.)

I have separate patches for jackson-databind and
jackson-datatype-guava; it's easy to apply to other packages as well.

This is a nice performance improvement as well; we no longer incur all
the overhead of causing the runtime to open and cache the .jar
(unzipping it
column11: etc.) just to read the VERSION.txt resource.\n\nIf the PackageVersion class doesn't exist
column12:
we'll of course fall back to the
existing test to get version info.

I confirmed using the Eclipse Memory Analyzer[1] that memory usage for
a large app I work on was reduced by about 5 MB with this fix (as well
as the jackson-databind and jackson-datatype-guava fixes).

Unit tests included.

[1] http://www.eclipse.org/mat/
"
